# .mailmap — display identity normalization for git history.
#
# This file does NOT change commit data. It only provides display aliases
# for tools that respect mailmap: `git log`, `git blame`, `git shortlog`,
# and the GitHub Contributors graph. Individual commit pages on GitHub
# still show whatever the original git author email maps to.
#
# Format: Canonical Name <canonical@email>  <commit-as-recorded@email>

# Normalize the canonical email's display name (handles GitHub web-edit
# commits which record the recorded name as the GH login, e.g. "stevefritz")
Stephen Fritz <steve.fritz@gmail.com>

# All Stephen variants → canonical identity
Stephen Fritz <steve.fritz@gmail.com>  <stephen@badger.blue>
Stephen Fritz <steve.fritz@gmail.com>  <stephen@stephenfritz.dev>
Stephen Fritz <steve.fritz@gmail.com>  <switchboard@stephenfritz.dev>
Stephen Fritz <steve.fritz@gmail.com>  <root@vps-526635cb.vps.ovh.ca>

# All CC worker variants → recognizable bot identity.
# These commits were made by Claude Code worker sessions before commit
# 41e72c3 wired up GIT_AUTHOR/COMMITTER injection per task. They were
# attributed to the SDK's default identity at the time. Mapping them to
# a stable Ouvrage Worker identity makes the contributor graph honest.
Ouvrage Worker <cc-worker@ouvrage.local>  <claude-code@anthropic.com>
Ouvrage Worker <cc-worker@ouvrage.local>  <foreman-worker@stephenfritz.dev>
Ouvrage Worker <cc-worker@ouvrage.local>  <worker@switchboard.local>
Ouvrage Worker <cc-worker@ouvrage.local>  <cc-worker@switchboard.local>
